Sure, here's an example of how Monte Carlo integration can be implemented in C++ to approximate the definite integral of a function:
```
#include <iostream>
#include <cstdlib>
#include <cmath>

double f(double x) {
    // function to integrate
    return x*x;
}

double monte_carlo_integration(double a, double b, int n) {
    double total = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        double x = ((double)rand() / RAND_MAX) * (b - a) + a;
        total += f(x);
    }
    double estimate = total / n * (b - a);
    return estimate;
}

int main() {
    double a = 0; // lower bound
    double b = 1; // upper bound
    int n = 10000; // number of random points
    double estimate = monte_carlo_integration(a, b, n);
    std::cout << "Estimate of the definite integral of f(x) from " << a << " to " << b << ": " << estimate << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```
This code will approximate the definite integral of f(x) = x^2 from 0 to 1 using 10000 random points. The function `monte_carlo_integration` takes 3 arguments : the lower bound of integration, upper bound of integration and number of random points. It returns the estimated value of the definite integral.

Please note that the accuracy of the estimate will depend on the number of random points used and the function being integrated. In general, larger number of points will provide a more accurate estimate.

One way to integrate f(x) = e^(-x^2/2) using Monte Carlo integration is to generate random points within the region of integration, and use the function to evaluate the points. The average value of the function at these points can then be used as an estimate of the definite integral.

Here is an example of how this could be implemented in C++:
```
#include <iostream>
#include <cstdlib>
#include <cmath>

double f(double x) {
    // function to integrate
    return exp(-x*x/2);
}

double monte_carlo_integration(double a, double b, int n) {
    double total = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        double x = ((double)rand() / RAND_MAX) * (b - a) + a;
        total += f(x);
    }
    double estimate = total / n * (b - a);
    return estimate;
}

int main() {
    double a = -3; // lower bound
    double b = 3; // upper bound
    int n = 10000; // number of random points
    double estimate = monte_carlo_integration(a, b, n);
    std::cout << "Estimate of the definite integral of f(x) from " << a << " to " << b << ": " << estimate << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```
This code will approximate the definite integral of f(x) = e^(-x^2/2) from -3 to 3 using 10000 random points.

Please note that this is not the exact integral of the function because the monte carlo integration is an approximation method. The error in the approximation will decrease as the number of samples increases.

One way to estimate the uncertainty of the integral computed using Monte Carlo integration is to use the standard deviation of the function values at the randomly generated points. Since the Monte Carlo estimate of the integral is the average of the function values at the random points, the standard deviation can be used to estimate the uncertainty of the estimate.

Here's an example of how this could be implemented in C++:
```
double monte_carlo_integration(double a, double b, int n) {
    double total = 0;
    double total_sq = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        double x = ((double)rand() / RAND_MAX) * (b - a) + a;
        double fx = f(x);
        total += fx;
        total_sq += fx * fx;
    }
    double estimate = total / n * (b - a);
    double variance = (total_sq / n - (total / n) * (total / n)) * (b - a) * (b - a);
    double standard_deviation = sqrt(variance);
    return estimate,standard_deviation;
}
```
In this implementation, in addition to the total of the function evaluated at the random points, I also keep track of the total of the squares of the function values. This will be used to calculate the variance and standard deviation of the function values at the random points.

The variance is calculated as (total\_sq/n - (total/n)^2) \* (b-a)^2 and the standard deviation is the square root of the variance.

The returned values are the estimated integral and the standard deviation of the estimated integral.

Please note that this method is an approximation, and the uncertainty in the estimate will decrease as the number of samples increases.
